```java
@Entity(name = &quot;Example&quot;)
@Table(name = &quot;example&quot;)
@SQLDelete(sql = &quot;&quot;&quot;
UPDATE example
SET deleted = true
WHERE
    id = ? AND
    version = ?
&quot;&quot;&quot;)
@Loader(namedQuery = &quot;findExampleById&quot;)
@NamedQuery(name = &quot;findExampleById&quot;, query = &quot;&quot;&quot;
select e
from Example e
where
    e.id = ?1 and
    e.deleted = false
&quot;&quot;&quot;)
@Where(clause = &quot;deleted = false&quot;)
public class Example extends SoftDeletable {
    @Id
    @GeneratedValue
    private Long id;

    @NaturalId
    private String name;

    @Version
    private short version;
}
```

`SoftDeletable` also looks like:

```java
@MappedSuperclass
public abstract class SoftDeletable {
    private boolean deleted;
}
```

Now whenever you try to delete an entity, hibernate will execute the `@SQLDelete` and set the deleted to true.

Also when trying to load an entity, the `@Where` clause will be applied filtering out soft deleted entities

More details and examples can be found on this article: [*Soft delete and JPA version property*][1]


